After the ranking phase, several hundred candidate peptides remain. To refine our selection and identify the top ten peptides with the most potent antibacterial properties, we train a regression model that can predict minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) values accurately. As the final stage in our pipeline, the model must minimize prediction bias in MIC. Through experimental comparison, we opt for the same fine-tuning strategy applied in the classification stage, using ESM-1b pre-trained model, freezing the parameters in the first 32 layers, and adjusting only the last layer. The final representation of a sequence is obtained from the [CLS] token of ESM-1b’s last layer, which is then input into a regression head composed of multiple MLP layers. Our rationale behind choosing this model architecture is that it achieves the lowest K-MSE score and delivers the best wet-lab results among all options explored. Details regarding hyperparameters can be found in our code. The employed loss function is defined as:5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
