				\begin{document}$$\%{{{\rm{cell\; viability}}}}=\frac{{{{{\rm{absorbance}}}}}_{{sample}}-{{{{\rm{absorbance}}}}}_{{blank}}}{{{{{\rm{absorbance}}}}}_{{negative}}-{{{{\rm{absorbance}}}}}_{{blank}}}\times 100$$\end{document}%cell viability=absorbancesample−absorbanceblankabsorbancenegative−absorbanceblank×100

Red blood cells (RBCs) from mice were used for this test. Hemolytic activity of the peptides was measured by first mixing the RBCs with the peptide solutions (n = 5). The mixtures were then incubated at 37 °C for 1 h. RBCs in PBS were used as the negative control, and 0.5% (w/v) Triton X-100 treated RBCs were used as the positive control. Afterward, the samples were centrifuged at 1500 g for 8 minutes. The absorbance of the supernatant was measured at 570 nm by a microplate reader. The percentage of hemolysis was calculated using the following equation.7\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
